More than 12,000 school students from the 4th to 8th classes have been involved in the project so far.
Proper eating and exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obesity children.
"Only half of those asked, for example, said that she had five times a day in breakfast-snack-dinner-snack-dinner, which is one of the basic assumptions of proper nutrition," is one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no cold evening
Experts point out that there are important and relative details for healthy development, such as regular family breakfast time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of school children eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding that tens of households don't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy fries are consumed more often in families of obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
While regularly more than 40 percent of the children asked about sports, their parents had less than half - 15 percent.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to build from offered options their own meals according to their own taste and self opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
There are a lot of flour, meaty and sweet dishes among their favorite dishes.
"In particular, the great popularity of sweet lemonade is alarming," says the final survey report.
Pasta won just over poultry for lunch as the main meal.
But the children practically didn't want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes is low.
Indicative health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In a number of cases, there is a significant shift of preference towards the principles of healthy nutrition for the survey participants who have completed a questionnaire after the end of the educational lecture Obesity," the results of the project indicate.
Markant, for example, was the case with sweet lemonade, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children have also checked poultry and fish as the main food of the day much more frequently in the questionnaire and would limit sweet foods and dumplings.
