How Travel Prices Developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were authorised in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, travel agencies sold in the vast majority only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sococa in Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility to travel to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime joined the West and the journeys of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were then very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that it was not possible for citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakians too) to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
The travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand the front overnight with a sleeping bag or to have a "good friend" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the journey to the West without a foreign promise.
However, by far the most often Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs have acquired and this habit still survives today.
The Czech travel has been experiencing a real revolution since 1989.
While the holidays in the NDR or Bulgaria were our maximum until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia by 1989, because it was a part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right at the end of the 1990s, visa waivers to neighbouring Western European countries took place, starting with a huge wave of short-term visits mainly in Austria and Germany.
Czechoslovakians couldn't take a long trip to the West, everyone wanted to take a look at it for a while.
For example, in Paris, the Czechs’ tours in tent parks slept, because our incomes did not allow us to pay for the hotel or guest house.
The typical feature of Czech travel was the carrying of own food, canned food, salami, etc. at this time to save itself.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely changeable Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists to buy the Western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with that, average wages increased, resulting in a further important moment around 1997.
Due to increased demand for travel, travel agencies have regularly started to prepare tours by charter air connections since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper thanks to the possibility of contracting quantitative discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already visa-free contact to practically all the advanced countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutional travel occurred right in 2000, when due to considerable demand was issued from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to the exoticy, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards they leave with Czech tourists direct charters to warm far countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are now visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutional development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled a visa for Czech tourists, and this brought our country to the forefront of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent for the first time in history more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and spent for the first time in history for one foreign holiday, including the cost of stay more than 15 thousand CZK per person.
