The emotionally strong new book by Peter Englund entitled Beauty and Grief: The Confidential History of the First World War begins with such a long list of performers when you turn your head.
One advice on how to behave at that moment: Carefully pull this page out and make a bookmark of it.
You will be very familiar with all people in Mr. Englund's novel story and this list will serve you as a navigation - like a beacon - in moments when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite aptly, as "antihistoric work".
It contains several well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it is almost missing ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, it explains the author, as more like "the book about what it was like". It mainly discusses "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beautiful and grief" combines war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flash like flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate, while others are quenched.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classic historical novels.
It adjusts the idea that World War I was just about the horrific trench fights in the West Front.
"Beautiful and grief" is also skillfully exploring other places where war dramas took place: Alps, Balkans, East Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve the problems of falling bee nests, must spend Christmas in the shade of the pyramids or face the presence of a fly tse-tse.
Almost from the beginning, it's a very touching reading.
The war will devour people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When the guns start shooting at a distance and you're the woman who's home with your kids, run away or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost nobody understands what's going on, even why the whole war was unleashed.
"The vacuum arising from a lack of facts," noted Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beautiful and sorrow" follows stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are taken from résumés, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives can sound scary and engaging, but thanks to the integration of small moments and details, they are completely lively and believable.
Many of them are talking about suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Replacements, substitutes everywhere."
"A coffee substitute, aluminium imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheep's fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato husks, shoes with wooden soles".
It mentions that there was "837 registered meat substitutes for sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
