Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of the government, Maria López Valdez increased unemployment and insecurity in Sinaloa, decreased foreign investment and the economy with them
The year 2011 will be recorded in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year of the government of Maria López Valdez, which is called the government of change. This government has brought great expectations in terms of economic progress, but due to adverse climate conditions at the beginning of the year, there has been no growth and even a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the growth potential of the state economy, led to a 3.6% reduction in economic activity in the first semester of this year, since there has been a historical decline of 31.16% in agriculture, which has disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage suffered by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, 78.03% of which was completely destroyed and partial damage was detected on the remaining 21.07%. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, maize and peas.
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state increased during the first three quarters of the year. From January to March, 55,053 inhabitants of the State of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August the average unemployment continued to rise to 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed. Thus, the number of unemployed rose by 18,969 compared to the first quarter.
Less liquidity
More factors can be explained for unemployment during the year in Sinaloa. According to Gerard López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps taken at the level of public policy.
"We are witnesses to growing unemployment, which is linked to various factors, such as the loss of liquidity in the market due to reduced resources due to legislation approved by Congress in the context of the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally encroach on dollars to make money, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Stop migration
López Cervantes stated that a demographic factor was also involved in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work has fallen to the United States, because of the difficult entry and then because, even if they get abroad, it's hard for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our country, and so unemployment is growing," he said.
Reliability
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the people employed in the state work without benefiting from social security management.
More features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and insecurity. In this administrative area there are the lowest wages from all over the country, as stated by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5 352 pesetas by September, deep below the national average of 7 375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
According to the Ministry of Finance, direct foreign investment amounted to $630,697, representing a fall of 87.74% over the same period in the previous year, compared to the amount of $543,312.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the Government mentions investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government asked the state Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. No debt gains were recorded by November, in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Maria López Valdés pointed out a lack of government management skills.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transforming Industry, stated that in 2011 there was a lack of reconciliation of the will of individual sectors, including the government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We need to work hard to get back the land we lost this year. In 2012 we need to double our efforts, we lacked harmonisation of all of our efforts, and in particular the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let us hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and reduced its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowing down of the economy, which did not quickly recover enough so that it could restore dynamism to an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year, we found ourselves deep under the expected forecasts", he said.
Re-definition of the mission
According to Theodore Salazar Uriarte, President of the Employment Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we are observing that work is being done. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state should be redefined, because it is important to mobilise all the potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has," he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in different areas, some progress has been made in the area of economic development, but it is important to establish a long-term plan," he said.
He stated that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is work done here and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead," he said.
