The possibility of adding 'voice by vote' appeared in this year's elections in Michoacán, where, according to the data published by the Programme of Preliminary Electoral Results (PREP), the difference between the first and second seats in the governor's elections is less than 27 percent, and this has not yet been counted by 879 votes from the total 6074 electoral districts.
In this context, the Chairman of the General Council of the Electoral Institute in Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, 9 November, the electoral authority approved a number of measures that should harmonise local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially confirmed his political constitution or his state election code or the electoral justice law, since the State Congress has approved reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force was due to expire in this parliamentary term and Governor Leonl Godoy Range has left their publication within the time limit set in the Official Journal Act, with any objections against them.
On 9 November, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative authority and declared the vote of the Head of State in respect of constitutional reforms for "undue and illegal", because it had no right to "not approve or veto".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied to the question of the possibility of adding "voice by voice" that thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council, it would be possible for the local electoral authority to carry out the partial and overall summation.
In this way, the partial summation of votes, one or more electoral packages, will be possible under the following conditions: the election results do not agree; there is no record of the summation and calculation in the relevant box, or the President does not have it at his disposal; or if errors and obvious violations of the electoral results have occurred.
In addition, the total recalculation of votes in all ballots will be possible if there is an indication that the difference between the potential winner of the elections and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever at the beginning of the session there is an explicit request from the representative of the party and/or the coalition which proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recalculation of votes will also be possible if, after a proper census, the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, and whenever there is an explicit request from a political party whose candidate has ended in second place, the electoral packages for which partial counting has been carried out will be eliminated.
It should be mentioned that in such a situation there is an election in Morelia, where according to the PREP there is a difference between the first and second place of less than 0.16%, although 129 of the total 923 electoral districts have not yet been added.
