The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance began research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute for Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts research to reveal a gene that causes obesity in children and young people. A research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youth" will provide results regarding overweight.
In a report by the Head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutrition professionals and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and students from the National Institute for Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without authority, can also participate in research. People can come to participate in the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where each council will carry out youth tests from 8am.
He stressed that the research began at the Sport Centre Cuauhtémoc (Mexico State) and that since 8 October this activity was also carried out in the Sport Centre Nezahualcoyolt (East of the Mexican State).
Once data are obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independencia Sport Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at Morelos Sport Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to trace risk factors to Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about the physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, circumference of the waist) are performed, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genes are determined (to identify genes that contribute to child obesity).
Cruz López stated that this research reflects health professionals’ concerns about the alarming increase in the child’s weight.
'The health polls carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that only a 77% increase in obesity occurred in boys and a 47% increase in girls. A dramatic increase also occurred in the case of overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one reason for finding indicators is that the population of the country is different from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African, which is reflected in genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general obesity genetics are commonly explained as inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefits of the participants are that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thereby determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark colour wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm suggests the probability that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar conditions.
In the meantime, the information is confidential, the doctors are giving it to their parents in writing, explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children’s illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentary life-styles that mean a lack of daily physical activity, day-to-day sitting before television and the use of means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight also causes a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no excavators in Asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture of better functionality, regardless of climate conditions and temperature
If the paving was properly cared for, almost 200,000 excavators would not need to be repaired after every rainy season in the Metropolitan region of Valle de México, Raphael Herrera Najer, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemicals (FQ) of UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavings were adequate, there would be significant restrictions on excavators or could even be completely removed.
In his lecture, the Technological cause of excavators, which he gave during the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his direction develops modified asphalts with polymers, which should produce a mixture of similar characteristics as asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najer believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of excavators.
He explained that the asphalt, the most difficult part of oil, is a group of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a large molecular mass, called asphalts, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called maltenes. Together they supply asphalt with a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it acts like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in solid condition, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperatures, warned the expert on chemical engineering.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with a flexible pavement consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers there is an asphalt insert, consisting of small stones covered in asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is filled with asphalt.
It is possible to decompose the forces in the pavement during driving or under pressure.
If it were a modified asphalt, it would have spread even better, says the chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert there would be the last layer called the cape, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also covered in asphalt.
