Austria
the inclusion of a golden rule on a balanced budget in the Constitution
The Government of the Great Coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats, which is in power in Austria, decided on Tuesday to enter the 'gold rule' of budgetary policy into the Constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid any reduction of the rating of Austria by credit rating agencies (AAA).
It was the socio-democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the conclusion of the ministerial meeting in a situation where the Austrian public debt is with its 74.6% high above the criteria of a maximum of 60% established by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the solvency of Austria were reduced by just one step from the AAA to the AA+, we would have to pay EUR 3 billion more on interest every year", argued the multi-officer and foreign minister, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria follows up on a request from the Eurozone Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where Heads of State or Government strongly asked for the reduction of the public deficit and the balance of public accounts to be entered in the Constitution or the law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is approaching the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a " Rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be able to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the federal countries as well as the municipalities will have to show a balanced budget.
The objective is to get public debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty in the period 2020/21.
