Nord Stream, the new Russian gas port to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe to Russia, led to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, began to work.
They must supply a gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part in the inauguration of the Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together by controlling the control valve of the Russian gas input to the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional Cuban metres of Russian gas will flow every year through the 1 224 km pipeline connecting the St Petersburg region to the Mecklenburg-Pomeranian Federal Land.
The second pipeline, which has to be completed at the end of 2012, will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is equal to the total French consumption.
The possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already being recalled.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries protested strongly against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At one point, these two countries are losing some power: the ability to push Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw most expressed this when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases with its support for this Russian project.
But it is at the price of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created a gap between the East and West Europeans.
Russia managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose bearings are nearing their end, just five years ago.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us", confirmed François Fillon at the opening ceremony and demonstrated at what point the large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete shell to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea in an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields from the Second World War.
"For safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffelvek, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations throughout its length.
One control platform should have been built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were little willing to see the Russian state company settled permanently off their coast.
"In case of a fault, we stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline shall escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since welds were designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The external gas pipeline check is carried out by an underwater robot drawn by a ship, while the inside of the gas pipeline is controlled by a device circulating inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
In the target, 3 m/s speeds will provide accurate information on possible metal parts deformations throughout the three-day journey.
The long-range gas pipeline was designed to work for 50 years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces for the implementation of this project.
The leadership remains Gazprom, which holds a 51% share.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as by the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, commissioned by the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
The company has its registered office in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely favourable.
Gasprom subsequently leased this company for five years by a contract that can be renewed, all its capacity for the transport of gas.
"Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported", states Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of the shareholder and 70% of the bank loans.
The total cost of work should be €7.4 billion for both pipelines.
Therefore, the investment costs for the GDF Suez group amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be returned to them, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
Gas pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
Ventiles at a height of 4,5 metres form the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors shall measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million an hour and 6 million in 2012.
